President Mohamed Morsi embarked on another poker game.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants unlimited powers to it, it has decided to play the ball.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else's opinion, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the next term.
Less than a week ago, the head of state awarded this ralcany meeting another two months to complete the necessary work.
For nearly two years, Egypt has been using a makeshift text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal conjecture.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the opposition's point of view, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium," continues to "violate his word" and "taps the law."
But his supporters assure that this is a means of turning the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should take place in two weeks' time.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention to clarify the text to the Egyptians by article.
It is also a way for the president to re-accept national and democratic legitimacy, while the country is roiled by protests.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially because this hastily organised vote puts the people before the ultimatum of the Egyptian people: 'Either you approve my text or I will leave unlimited powers', which should otherwise end after the new constitution is approved.
And in this particular atmosphere yesterday, the 85 members of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was announced, they slammed through the door, saying they had no way of getting their views known.
Defenders of human rights, civil society or members of religious minorities have imitated their move.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 alternate replacements were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising then that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators went on to pause that one of the few disputes revolved around the day... a prayer class when some committee members took the view that the hours in the conference room were not properly arranged.
The text, which was still to be put to the vote last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains the same as that of the 1971 constitution, and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, were hopeful to replace the term "cars" with the term "rules," which would allow for a more stringent application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article was not corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egypt's society.
"Hyrability," the Liberals object, seeing only a rhetorical problem.
In their view, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus, in particular, on Article 220, which entrust the University of al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular to the issues of the monitoring of the conformity of the laws with sharia law.
According to Egyptian expert Sophie Pommier, this is unsettling because "persons called to comment are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
