The concerns of the Liberals are further fuelled by the fact that the next university rector should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, there has been no specific religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulamas, but university staff, many of whom have studied in French schools," says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a job on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be contradictions about the interpretation of Article 220 because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
There is a reference in particular to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, ed.].
And in the future, the question of the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment may be.
The text approved yesterday is highly criticized in addition to the religious sites because of the expanded powers that are granted to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction in them compared to the former regime.
Another contentious place: the powers vested in the military.
In line with the wishes of the military's representatives, the defence budget will not be verified by parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
