In an interview for Aktuálně.cz, the vice-president of the Supreme Audit Office, Miloslav Kala, says so.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be the right thing to do - that's what I think is missing from us," Kala comments on the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also indicated by the joint control of Czech and German controllers.
As an example of incorrect practice, he cites Petr Nečas's approach to the so-called "charticcze."
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother businessmen with his checks - so is he banned or allowed?
"The law must be set up somehow, and if it does, if it does, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activities of the office, which is obliged to go to check and enforce obligations," Kala says.
At a meeting of the Audit Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke of a joint project between the Czech and German parties, comparing the legislation on public procurement in both countries.
What exactly was going on?
This is a parallel check, which we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, the point is that European legislation regulates how to deal with public procurement, followed by individual national legislation and then by the practice itself.
We have put all of this together, and although the control is not yet terminated, we have shown very interesting differences - in general, the legislation is perhaps "stillar and more perfect" in our country, but the practice itself is better in some parameters.
So it is confirmed that it is not enough to create more accurate rules over and over again, but it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually help you do, what does it mean to you?
It is such joint control that could contribute to us ceasing our efforts to refine the laws, lowering and improving the limits when it does not have such a positive impact.
Economy means getting the appropriate thing as a reasonable thing (which does not always mean the lowest) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal conduct.
But by lowering the contract limit, we do not necessarily achieve this.
Maybe the system will be overwhelmed with so much "paper" that those who want to look for holes in that system will draw on it a lot more easily than if the limit stayed higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the transfer of legislation to practice public procurement.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is the office similar to our SAO, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, just as the SAO operates there the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organised in a similar way to us, also has a college, only forms in a slightly different way, but in principle the two authorities act similarly.
The powers are also similar to some extent, but in the fact that Germany has a federal arrangement, so it has these accounting courts at the level of the various federal states - in this, the system differs from ours a bit.
The BRH can only control the federal money, in our country, by state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the county and municipalities, are checked there from the level of the federal accounting courts.
As far as legislation there is, that is easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without specific data, however in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly not possible to say that it is better at everything.
So is it necessary that they have better controllers?
I'm sure not, but I'm saying again, I don't like that kind of comparisons.
But it has to be said that even the countries we see as a role model face a whole range of problems.
Otherwise, it wouldn't be any conducive to them to cooperate with our office, would it?
As for domestic legislation, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, are there any effect on its effects?
Since the validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in the inspection events in our country.
Because we are doing ex-post checks, we need to expect some delays.
We are only seeing this so far in the process of preparing future controls - we have started our new "detention of risk-tripatibility" tool, through which we have laced almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - there, of course, the changes will be manifested there, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tenders will be adjusted and the like.
So you consider the approval of this law to be more of a benefit or a further burden on the red tape system?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope that this will be confirmed.
A problem that may arise here that the rules will be "stretched" and it will not be possible to abide by them.
Already under the functioning of the previous rules, the audited persons are bound by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the Regional Council) to the fact that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act entails a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it therefore worth making the law tightening up in this way?
Not in this way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to challenge and abuse it, and not punish those who commit a formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more pressure on the bureaucracy.
Then how do we get out of it?
Let's show where the road doesn't go.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not harass entrepreneurs by inspecting the so-called 'spirit system' - and what does that mean?
Švarcsystém is forbidden or allowed?
The law must be set up somehow, and if it does forbid something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the work of the office, which is obliged to go to check and enforce obligations.
He can say, "Let's change the law and we'll pass it up," but he can't say we're going to act like nothing.
The Public Procurement Act has fairly strict rules on how to be formally implemented - which is correct to protect the public tender.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best bid is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be right - that's what I think is missing from us.
