Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at concerts
What do you think of the end of the world coming to the end of the world in less than a month?
It's just one of the other alarms that we humans like to catch on.
Together with the band The Tap Tap, we make more fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world who can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December, you will have a completely unique project of three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce it to the readers more closely?
This is a nationwide fundraiser that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to tap the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on December 20 at 9 p.m., there will be 3 concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end around the time the Mayan calendar is about the end of the time-space on Kiribati Island in the Pacific, which is 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally it was probably my idea, then we invented everything together with our artist Honza Augusta.
In addition to accumulating enough positive energy and preventing the end of the world, we also want to reflect with the public on the state in which we will one day pass this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items of shoes, T-shirts, bags or original germs against the end of the world, which are purchased at www.e-tap.cz, people can also support us.
The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anti-end anthem called "The End of the World Cancelled."
It is already very popular on YouTube, will it also be heard at these benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, that is, if we all succeeds and the end of the world does not come to an end...
It is sung by all performers at all three concerts in parallel.
The hymns will suddenly also be linked in a unique live broadcast on Czech Television.
The words for this song were written and the lead role of Jesus in the clip is played by Tomáš Hanák, it is also sung by Xindl X...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, given that we organize a lot of fundraising events and concerts...
We are trying to engage them intensively in these projects.
It turns out that most of them are interested and entertaining to work with us.
What will the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world go for?
The equipment of the Studeo barrier-free education centre, which we have been implementing with the civic association Tap in the Jedlička Institute for the sixth year.
School students at the Jedlička Institute regularly receive lecturers and attend to them in activities they enjoy and interest.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the lecturers themselves, so we try to allow them to do so in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be created in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Each concert will feature several musical groups and performers.
How did you choose them?
We tried to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere will perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bangoo and Jiří Suchý.
Read all the details at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar "bombastic events" for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, so here too we will certainly prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests.
We would also like to play at the Czech Nationals in New York next year, and I personally, while we are in the US, I would like to link it to performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalist, you have so far performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow, for example.
The Tap Tap is nevertheless a group made up of handicapped people.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it first appears.
We have five members on an electric cart, their carts have to travel in the luggage compartment, then, of course, we are lugging with us a large amount of cargo and boxes of tools...
However, so far it has always been done without any problems, with CSA and British Airways being well prepared for us that I have often wondered.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was without problems.
Exports abroad make you compare how different different ones are in barrier-free, public access to the handicapped and the like.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than ours, we have just seen in Russia that in the east everything is still in the very beginning.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person to move on an electric cart in the city centre.
It doesn't even apply to such obviousness, such as to give a wheelchair user first in an elevator.
Fortunately, civic associations are already being formed there, trying to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And what, on the other hand, do we still have to catch up with more advanced countries?
There are a lot of things we're still behind in...
But it is important to mention that improving and improving the situation is always dependent on the efforts of the people involved.
In both London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a heavy handicap to move independently in public, to go to the toilet, to the museum, to wherever...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, in this we are a little bit ahead with The Tap Tap!
Respecting the public or barrier-free is one thing, but it is only when we become important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers that things start to change in earnest.
So far, these are isolated cases of people with strong will.
The band The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but let's go back a few years later, what made you start it in 1998?
I joined as a tutor at the Jedlička Institute, where I had many young people around who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play the saxophone, among other things, I started a special-interest music club with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our presenter Láďa Angelovič says, it has gotten a little out of hand (laughter).
But the popularity came in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us when we started to connect with the well-known singers and also to actively work to promote the band.
We realized that a job that is not visible to us is basically like it didn't exist.
In addition, thanks to the contributions from the European Union, we can afford quality tutors, equipment and so on.
Was your goal to make it this high with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something differently.
Showbusiness is crowded with things where one imitates the other.
It's logical in a way, it's all new to be accepted cautiously, and it takes a long time.
Things that are unique are very few, but I daresay Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression in a person who sees us for the first time is, of course, regret, that's natural...
But the regret is completely in vain, because people with disabilities are not suffering from all the abandoned beings we must be sorry for.
These are people who can live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the means to do so.
I'm saying that when people with a handicap get something done, it's not just a shift for them, it's for the whole company.
Did this success also help that you are a strict boss, as many people have called you?
When we want to do quality jobs, we have to be uncompromising about many things and require a certain discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic image and a head in the clouds, and when they find out they have to go to the exam for a twice-week exam, come to the product and spend a lot of time on the road to the concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and who wants to achieve something.
The band Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them were at her beginnings in 1998?
Only one Lada Angelovich.
We're an open group, people are leaving and coming, you can't stop it.
Whoever has the will and the taste always has the door open with us
