This is the case for Anta Wijay, one of the 400 miners who make his living by conquering sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, they have to fry every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gases escape from the inside of the Earth and pass into a solid state when in contact with the air.
After chopped up large sulfur blocks, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, they carry them on the shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone trails.
The top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 metres, is only 250 metres, but it takes the exhausted carriers to climb up at the turtles' pace, as they keep their balance and carefully contemplate their steps to avoid slippageing and crashing into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their life, as happened to a French tourist who collapsed years ago from the rocks of Kawah Ijen.
The miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for each kilo of sulfur they extract
When they're up, they make their way past the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in the circus, and wearily carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company has placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 metres.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has benefited from the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupies (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even whitening of sugar.
"Because we normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes the three journeys a day.
One trip takes him three hours and is destroyed at the end, but he can earn 13138,000 rupees (€11.5) per day.
While this seems to be a negligible amount for such inhumane efforts, it is three times what he would make in the field.
"The daily wage for the miners is very high here. For example, collecting coffee is paid for 15,000 rupees (€1.2) per day, and the salary per fortnight is two million rupees (€166))," explains the porter who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.2) per day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason, which is as convincing in Indonesia as the sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, it's hard to breathe, coughs all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks living in the Kawah Ijen volcano three times a day, the sulfur of which has already begun to take its toll on it, even though his face is protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's hard to breathe, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I will be working for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises more than a decent English.
This likeable and intelligent young man, troubled by the fate, could be a tourist guide, waiter or a hotel receptionist, and instead does the work of a carrier.
She shares a dirty wooden hut with other porters and gets up at two o'clock every day because the sulfur continues to flail at night and its distinctive yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness of the phrase, the Anto's pharate, illuminating his way with a small flashlight that he has attached to his helmet and has bought it with his own money.
About 400 porters carry on the shoulders of a sulfur basket from the bottom of the crater
Although the company has high incomes, it has not mechanised the sulfur mining to cost savings, nor does it provide the carriers working on their own and with such effort, no equipment.
In fact, they do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (€2.5) from the photography supplement, which, together with the ticket for 15,000 rupees (€1.2), is collected by the nature park keepers from the tourists arriving to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the cattle, and not for the people," says Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old carrier who has worked at Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left the schools.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will keep working, "as long as possible" because he needs the education of his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life
Although the sulphur burns its throat and stings in its eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and tramples the miners in the dense fumes that emanate from the volcano, the miners are so hard to say that none of them complains that they suffer from serious illnesses... but this is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pains and wounds on the shoulders caused by the weight of the baskets.
The unainik who balances his basket on his back can only load 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day he and his colleagues dig out 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which the three trucks then take the steep route between the thicket to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometres away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik declares, opening a wide mouth in which several teeth are missing.
Of his five sons, the eldest, a 30-year-old, also makes his living by mining the sulfur.
Time passes, but the incessant misery of one of the world's most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans are blamed for not having children, careers, stress, and the cost of living and education.
"The people of Singapore need to grow."
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot. Let's fulfill our civic duty and we will be born a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of the ad for menthol sittings, but still - or perhaps because of it - the video in Singapore earlier this year was massively expanded to include on YouTube.
These theorems are part of a rap that uses local innuendoes like "let's beech in the oven" as a mockery of the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes to highlight the problem with this ad in a witty way.
The agency's artistic director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the influence of music to make people "a civic duty" done to work out.
"This is entirely an issue of the Internet, so it must have been fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in reproducing our population, so we felt that this was a topic that we had to touch.
We knew the government was trying to do a lot of things like expanding pheromone perfume or organizing dating parties.
Many of these ideas might have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative possible thing, such as the composition of rap, to solve the problem."
1.2 children
Whoever doesn't take it too lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and allocates financial benefits.
But all these measures have had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy urban state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
The fertility rate in Singapore, with a view to stratification of the population, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the fertility rate exceeded the value of the birth rate was as a rate of renewal, in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans have no more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Department of Marriage and the Family of the National Office for Population says it's for "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"People have a wider range of life's goals and priorities at their disposal, it's not just a wedding and a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increasing the number of single people and the postponement of marriage and the procuring of children. The result is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
While immigration policy involved efforts to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against a decline in population, this has provoked resentment among local residents.
Some of the Singaporean websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticised for maintaining low pay and a lack of effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the governing Singapore party recorded its worst election result since independence began last year.
After the election, there was an effort to address the problem with quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected aftermessage
While the fall in the birth rate has seen effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health-care spending, and immigration policies, there have also been some unexpected consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying to keep so many small houses from being built.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Office for Urban Development has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as the "footbox" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These apartments have an area of 46 square metres and have been a great success in salesmanship.
Nevertheless, it is feared that these apartments can support the bachelor's lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the property developer EL Developers, says their "shoisbox" sells far faster than bigger houses.
"They're more popular, selling for days to weeks faster than larger-scale houses.
That's why they're much better for our cash flow."
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously capped when they wanted to offer too many small houses in a single project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules could be aimed at increasing the birth rate of the nation, a conversation with the Singaporeans working in the financial district of the city centre suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as are education, so many people postpone it," says the young official.
"The others have children.
But for me it is important to rely on my own money and time," says another, about 20-year-old.
Both men and women mention their careers, stress and cost of living and their education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So, however the government is trying to force the citizens to have children, it is the Singaporeans who have the last word on starting a family.
What is a private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to the vocabulary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something that is of a personal nature or "the area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disturbance."
What is privacy for a man under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes on the internet matters he would certainly not have told anyone in his normal communications?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent users of the Internet.
In four cases, they considered the notion of privacy to be "something entirely of its own" on a personal level and a "user name and password" if it was social networks.
"My biggest secret I would not release," says 10-year-old Jorge, in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," he claims.
"On FB I give nice pictures or pictures of us playing.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that would make a mockery of someone," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most are related.
Among them is the mother, who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I started an Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never have accepted a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even be interested if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on the Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks, and admits to the latest network that he doesn't know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not worried about it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them pointed him out to him, nor did he want his address or phone number.
"If they urged me or demanded it from me, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
Jose made the call to Ask after reading the Twitter recommendation.
This boy is no stranger to experience with what is now called cyberbullying (cyberbullying).
"The well-known friend was blackmailed on the social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never learned who it was," he confirms.
The victim, according to Jose, did not get out of the account.
"She just activated her private mode."
Then he explains a series of steps to safely set the account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would do that if someone bothered me or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he claims.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate in Education and Teaching, believes that, in order to get to the right orientation of children and adolescents in social networks, they must understand that the main aim of these networks is to inform.
He states that: "The Internet originated as a means of seeking information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of teaching at Yale University and the author of the article Digital Reagents and digital immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born during the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, yet we are still learning," he says.
He explains that it is a complex subject "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what the other way around is not, at an age when they are not yet mature for it."
Also, to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - to be deliberate, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: There are some things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or: Would you like to see someone posting your picture as you posted a friend's?
You know what the others are publishing about you?
When you tag the people in the pictures of the celebrations, did you ask these people's permission?
And one more: Do they all want to know what you're doing right now?
The next point is to make them realise that they have to behave in the internet environment the same way they do outside of it.
It's the same rules.
"You are governed by respect, morality and other principles outside the internet, and one should be the same on social networks," he claims.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-grade teacher and an educational adviser, explains the need for children's parents to read the rules of social networks carefully.
"If they understand every trickiness, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences that setting up an online account can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional "not to talk to strangers" rule.
South America Summit Ends and the Lima Declaration Not Discounted
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru today without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and was reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
The eahead agency has repeatedly attempted to gain access to a document signed at the sixth meeting of the heads of state or government of Unasur, but representatives of both the Foreign Ministry and the presidential office, who initially stipulated that it would be published after the summit, said it would be published later on the Peruvian government's website.
They also said the content was released by Peru's President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists had their access to information restricted throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential assembly was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message "confidential session, sound transmission to be avoided."
A small amount of information available to the journalists was provided by the press officers of some of the governments who were present, but not the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document published during the meeting was a list of attending presidents, which prompted the displease of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent out an email to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but this is just a statement by President Humala and not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-País Orabes Árabes) and, even on this occasion, the initially promised Lima Declaration was not released, although it was keenly required by the press.
The official ASPA website shows that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but to completely prevent the supply of information.
The summit ended with, among other things, a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
President of Peru Ollanta Humala and President of Chile Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which on Monday would begin hearing the dispute launched by Lima against Santiago.
"We will subtract and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are hearing in this international court today," President Humala and his Chilean counterpart said.
"The chil was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, agreements and international courts," Piñera said, greeting President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that he would submit to the International Court of Justice's ruling was made public after Colombia's adopted the Bogota Pact this week, in submitting to the judgments of the International Court of Justice that ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered the decision to be completely flawed.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning speeches and the end of the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read out the final document, which reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and action was planned for 31 projects among South American countries, with investment of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the member countries of UNASUR would take "important steps towards the target of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are being extended."
He informed that actions were being supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and the cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, "the economic consolidation (Latin America) has no winning essence, but is to be used to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport links between different South American locations, especially rural and border areas... to make our countries more interconnected and create new economic ties," the Peruvian president said in a reading speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects involved Peru and the transiposites of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two related to a better association with Ecuador, but he did not give further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return it to the Union of South American Nations" from which it is currently excluded.
Another of the issues highlighted by the summit was that Latin America would remain a prosperous and peaceful area, which is whole and has good neighbourhood relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to hear with respect the judgment of the International Court of Justice concerning the dispute over the maritime border dispute contested by Bogotá.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will discuss all the solutions, none are excluded, nor the treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilised and considerate possible form possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday to attend the inauguration of the country's president, Enrique Peña Niet.
As part of the summit, the EU's defence ministers met tentatively to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which seeks to strengthen the dialogue and consensus on the field of defence.
UNASUR members are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the last mentioned country is currently out of the question.
Peru is the interim president of this regional bloc.
