AIDS victims are now the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of his test was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if a bolt of lightning hit me," he tells me, recalling the moment of truth, which the doctor tried to "slighten" a little, but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his own sickness to his own shoulders and began to inform himself of it. With such dedication that he's already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the most so-called HIV patients at the Civic Hospital in Guadalajara (HCG), which he arrived in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there were a lot of doubt, little treatment and a greater stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
At the time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and to live fully.
However, there are a lot of people who are unaware of their illness and only come when the virus caused the body's destruction and has exhausted the immune system, and they then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS, or at least from the first documented cases, "it has been a major achievement for the patient's life expectancy to start treatment in a timely and appropriate manner," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, saying that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
HIV/AIDS addenict and specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full-fledged life depends on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, better off being those who do not use drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years and people with 500 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years.
Simply put, this means that those who are diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, "at to live without problems until 75 years of age," the doctor explained in the interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years.
Although the mortality rate has decreased significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAAIDS) Joint Programbook (UNAIDS) Joint Programbook), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since AIDS was discovered, according to national statistics.
255 people died in the state of Jalisco alone in 2011 and 187 so far until this May. However, since 2005, universal access to antiretroviral agents has been provided.
- Why do people continue to die from the disease?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, this is how it happens in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have not exhausted the stock of pharmaceuticals. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they don't know the state of the disease, or in the late stages of the disease."
Adds a convincing statement: "Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection already emerges. The only thing that needs to be done to be able to do more in order to be able to influence overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, so we need to offer tests on a large scale to identify the disease to all those who ask for it."
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the StateAIDS Council in the state of Jalisco, as well as with patients like Fabrizio, who came to have his tests done at the private laboratory simply because his friend did it, and despite his low age, he had already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather have a run-in three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
The change was for the better, healthy, I exercise, I take medication."
To this day, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
"I live a normal life like anyone.
